maps.name: Systems Map
maps.description:
# The Whole Student

## A systematic analysis of the mental health challenge ecosystems on college campuses.

### Aaron Carpenter, Lily Goldberg, Riley Harper, Deborah Shoola, Rachel Smith, Hanqi Xiao

We developed a systems map that presents the problems, factors, variables, and structures that contribute to the mental health crisis on college campuses, with the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill (UNC) acting as a case study. 

With over 18,000 undergraduate students, UNC is a vibrant and dynamic community, but it is also one where mental health challenges can have a significant impact on students' lives. In the fall of 2021, the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill witnessed 2 student suicides. Approximately one in four UNC students have reported experiencing symptoms of depression, and one in six have reported experiencing symptoms of anxiety. Hiring more college counselors to treat, refer, and triage students in crisis is a Sisyphean task; the root causes of the college mental health crisis at UNC lie deeper, and more upstream, than a well-trained therapist can fix. 

We identified that there are multiple drivers and root causes within each system  social, environmental, individual, and institutional  that contribute to an ecosystem of mental health challenges on college campuses while facilitating and reinforcing each other to trap undergraduate students in cycles of powerlessness. We separated this complex web of factors into 5 sectors that add up to make a whole student: individual student factors, student social networks, the classroom, culture, attitudes, and beliefs, and barriers to accessing mental health support.
